(1510, 1, '2017-01-17 10:55:48', '2017-01-17 10:55:48', 'This is an example page. It\'s different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:\n\n<blockquote>Hi there! I\'m a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my website. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like pi&#241;a coladas. (And gettin\' caught in the rain.)</blockquote>\n\n...or something like this:\n\n<blockquote>The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.</blockquote>\n\nAs a new WordPress user, you should go to <a href="http://localhost:8888/teaching/wp-admin/">your dashboard</a> to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!', 'Sample Page', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-01-17 10:55:48', '2017-01-17 10:55:48', '', 2, 'http://localhost:8888/teaching/2017/01/17/2-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1511, 1, '2017-01-17 10:57:08', '2017-01-17 10:57:08', 'Welcome to WordPress. This is your first post. Edit or delete it, then start writing!', 'Hello world!', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-01-17 10:57:08', '2017-01-17 10:57:08', '', 1, 'http://localhost:8888/teaching/2017/01/17/1-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1512, 1, '2017-01-17 12:03:35', '2017-01-17 12:03:35', 'Welcome to Teaching to Freedom. I am a teacher (secondary maths) and have always had a keen interest in the areas of money and finance. I have always held a dream to have saved enough money to be able to retire early or to earn enough passive income so that I can do the things in life that I most enjoy, the things that I find I am not able to do whilst working full time.\r\nAbout two years ago, I read the book The Millionaire Teacher which I would recommend to anyone wanting to take control of their finances.\r\nI have just bought a new house, a car and last year, welcomed my first child, yet, I am still able to save over 50% of my teacher’s salary each month.\r\nI hope that my blog will show that you do not have to earn a six-figure salary in order to save a lot of money and that you can retire early on your own terms.\r\n\r\nI love teaching and inspiring the younger generation and have gained so many skills over the years. I have used these planning, organisational and time management skills to develop my own work/life agenda and by following this plan, quite soon I will be in a position to work completely on my own terms.\r\nOf course, I do not expect everyone to follow my frugal ways but I do hope that you can learn how to make your money work for you.\r\n\r\nAfter reading several finance blogs and ‘The Millionaire Teacher,’ I soon realised that I was going wrong with the way that I treated my money.\r\nI have made many mistakes with the spending of my money over the years; constantly wanting to appear as if I had more money even though I actually had very little.\r\nI was brought up in a normal middle class family and as I went through school I never really focused on my studies and was constantly met with the classic saying from my teachers such as, "If only he tried." So yes, lots of regrets when it comes to my education and, ironically, I am now lecturing students on the very things that I never did at school.\r\nSo, I went into teaching, not that I ever wanted to become a teacher because my thoughts were that teachers are all quite hard up (as can be many people’s view). Actually, come to think of it, standing in front of a class of children was a nightmare for me. But it was around the 2008/2009 financial crisis and it was a secure job, so a teacher I became.\r\nI remember at the beginning of my teaching career, I was earning around £1350 per month and probably spending a lot more than that each month.\r\nAfter just one year, I bought a sports car (on finance) which was costing me £500 a month and then I was blowing the rest on nights’ out.\r\n\r\nIt was around this time that I started dating my current other half (Mrs TTF). Again, to impress her, I was spending far beyond my means, staying at 5 star hotels and eating at exclusive restaurants. In the back of my mind, I always wanted to become financially independent, but just didn’t know how to get there.\r\n\r\nHowever, last August we welcomed our first child and I consider that this was a turning point in my life and would prove to be a change for the better.\r\n\r\nFast forward to now and I am saving over 50% of my monthly income consistently and have become well versed in making, saving and spending money.\r\nIt is these life changing experiences that I would like to share with you.', 'About author', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'about-author', '', '', '2017-01-17 12:09:12', '2017-01-17 12:09:12', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/teaching/?page_id=1512', 0, 'page', '', 0),
